WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.960
Welcome, everyone, to the Data Science Hangout. If this is your first time joining, this is

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:15.960
an open space for the whole data science community to connect and chat about data science leadership,

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:20.559
what's going on in the world of data science, and really just questions you're all facing

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:25.480
as well. So we really want to create a space where everybody can participate and we can

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:31.040
hear from everyone. So there are multiple ways that you can jump in the conversation

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:36.680
and ask questions. You could jump in live, you can put questions in the chat. And then

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:42.439
we also have a Slido link where you could ask anonymous questions too. So the session

00:00:42.439 --> 00:00:48.160
will be recorded and shared up to YouTube. So you can always use the anonymous way of

00:00:48.160 --> 00:00:54.279
asking questions if you prefer to not be part of that. Also, if you want to ask a question

00:00:54.279 --> 00:01:00.480
in the chat, and maybe you're in a crowded, loud room, and you want me to read that out,

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:04.360
you can just put a little star at the end of it as well. And I'll know to read that

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:11.160
for you. But thank you all so much for joining. I'm so excited to be joined by my co host

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:17.800
for today, who you may have seen as an attendee on a few of the past sessions, Aliyah Wakil.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:24.760
Aliyah is a epidemiology team lead at the Texas Department of State Health Services.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:29.879
And Aliyah, I'd love to just kind of turn it over to you first to just introduce yourself

00:01:29.879 --> 00:01:33.559
and share a bit about some of the work that you do on your team, if that's okay.

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:39.720
Yeah, sure. So thank you so much, Rachel. So like Rachel said, I am an epidemiologist.

00:01:40.519 --> 00:01:46.839
The majority of my experience has been in government. So I've worked at the federal level.

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:51.080
I had an opportunity to work with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

00:01:52.199 --> 00:01:57.480
And I have also worked at the state level. And I'm actually excited because I'm currently

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:03.400
transitioning into a new role from an epidemiologist, epidemiology team lead

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:10.119
with the Texas Department of State Health Services to an analytics manager position,

00:02:10.119 --> 00:02:19.000
which is really exciting. So right now, the position that I'm in is that we are developing

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:27.000
a center of public health informatics. And as an analytics manager, I have the opportunity

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.399
to work with our stakeholders that are in the community, but also within the agency,

00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:42.919
and to really develop our skills and our knowledge around how do we leverage working with data and

00:02:42.919 --> 00:02:49.320
public health to really combat a lot of public health issues within the state. And then also

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:58.119
building a community that really is comfortable with working with data. So that includes managing,

00:02:58.119 --> 00:03:06.279
analyzing, and most importantly, communicating data. So right now, my team is tasked with

00:03:06.279 --> 00:03:14.360
building out not only our analytic abilities, but also developing the workforce that we collaborate

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:20.279
really closely. So I think that's really been exciting for me, just trying to figure out

00:03:20.279 --> 00:03:28.679
strategies to get people who maybe they aren't really, they don't really have those hard technical

00:03:28.679 --> 00:03:32.919
skills and working with data, but they do use data for like their strategic planning,

00:03:33.639 --> 00:03:40.440
to make decisions. So really just empowering them to leverage data in their everyday work.

00:03:42.199 --> 00:03:46.839
That's awesome. And I know one of the things you said that you're most passionate about is being

00:03:46.839 --> 00:03:52.839
able to bring data science to everybody. And I'm just curious, what are some of the strategies that

00:03:52.839 --> 00:04:04.520
you're taking to do that? Yeah, so most recently, I really got on board with data literacy. So if

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:11.720
everyone isn't familiar with data literacy, it's the ability to read, work with, analyze,

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:17.480
communicate, and argue with data. So it is, I would say it's like a trending topic right now.

00:04:18.359 --> 00:04:24.440
And data literacy, in my mind, is really just meant for everyone. It's not just meant for

00:04:25.079 --> 00:04:30.679
the epidemiologists like myself, who have a strong research background, or data analysts,

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:40.040
but it's also meant for business leaders and even nurses, consultants, medical doctors.

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:45.959
Again, I work in public health, so a lot of my references might be health-related. But that it

00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:53.320
is for everyone, that everyone can utilize these skills and benefit from just knowing some

00:04:53.320 --> 00:05:02.119
foundations around how do I interpret results that are presented in some literature,

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:10.679
or even presented in news articles. And I would say that right now, a couple of the strategies

00:05:10.679 --> 00:05:17.720
that we are implementing, first is just getting an understanding of where other teams are in their

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:25.399
abilities and in their knowledge. So we are data folks, so we're surveying, we're putting out

00:05:25.399 --> 00:05:32.839
assessments, giving people the opportunity to let us know what kind of programs that they have

00:05:32.839 --> 00:05:38.600
experience with, what is their level of comfort working in some of these programs, which includes

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:49.559
SAS, Excel, Tableau, R, RStudio. And then also, are they open to learning other programs? So we are

00:05:49.559 --> 00:05:57.239
also, with the Center of Public Health Informatics, we're expanding to really centralize

00:05:57.239 --> 00:06:03.799
all of the data that we use and all the technologies that we use, and moving forward to

00:06:03.799 --> 00:06:10.920
become a bit more data science-centered. So we're really trying to make a push from those that

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:17.239
have traditionally worked in SAS to start using R and RStudio. Those that traditionally, you know,

00:06:17.239 --> 00:06:23.160
work in Excel and have those foundations, and maybe, you know, they are able to create charts

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:30.760
in Excel to start moving towards using Tableau. So things like that. So as far as just getting a

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:36.440
lay of the land, doing assessments and surveys, we'll also be creating some metrics for us

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:44.600
to be able to monitor and track over time to see how, you know, from baseline

00:06:46.279 --> 00:06:51.959
to whenever we want to survey it again to actually see if people are kind of making

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:57.000
some progress towards understanding these technologies. And we also are,

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:06.519
we are creating communities around sharing knowledge. So we will be developing webinars

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:15.559
that we'll host maybe monthly, quarterly, where people can come join. We'll have speakers that

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:21.399
are possibly talking about what they're doing in R or some visualizations that they're doing in

00:07:21.399 --> 00:07:30.279
Tableau. And then also holding office hours with some of our experts on our team. We do have like

00:07:30.279 --> 00:07:35.640
Tableau coordinators. So just making sure that they're available for people that are interested

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:40.760
and if they are working on a project that they can receive some guidance and some consultation

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:48.600
on a project that they're working with. And then also, we were able to procure agency-wide

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:56.920
licenses for DataCamp. So DataCamp is a platform like Coursera, but we do have the

00:07:56.920 --> 00:08:04.200
enterprise access. So we have access to all the courses that include, you know, how to develop

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:11.799
dashboards, courses on machine learning and predictive analytics, and also some courses

00:08:11.799 --> 00:08:18.839
around theories and just building that knowledge of how to work with data. So yeah, so those are

00:08:18.839 --> 00:08:24.200
like a couple of things that that we're working on now. Nice. And so I know you said you're just

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:30.279
launching some of those webinars too. How are you going about like sharing it with everybody and

00:08:30.279 --> 00:08:37.000
launching the program? So that is a really good question. I will say that I'm happy that we're in

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:45.239
a position to where we plan on it being iterative. So really just, you know, let's see what works.

00:08:45.239 --> 00:08:53.400
If it doesn't work, let's revisit and try something else. So right now, we have identified

00:08:54.359 --> 00:09:01.880
a team of, I believe that they are a disease prevention team, and they're actually

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:09.719
interested in learning a bit more about Tableau and how to do some dashboard building. So we do

00:09:09.719 --> 00:09:17.080
have a Tableau coordinator who will start, he'll actually develop a webinar based off of some of

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:23.320
the skills that they already have, so he can get an idea of where they are, and he'll create a webinar

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:28.280
for them. And I would say that it'll be like a pilot just to see how it goes with them, and if

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:35.239
it goes well, then this is something that will hopefully expand to other teams. And the ways

00:09:35.239 --> 00:09:43.719
that we'll communicate will of course be through email, but we also have weekly meetings that we

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:51.479
are able to communicate with teams that are, it's like an all-hands-on-deck meeting weekly, so we're

00:09:51.479 --> 00:09:57.000
able to communicate with other people that aren't on our teams. So this would just be

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:03.799
another way for us to put it out there, let them know what we're doing, how they can join us,

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:12.200
and just letting them know our vision and how we do plan on really supporting them in this expansion

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:18.039
of trying to build up our data knowledge and our skills. That's great. I see there's a lot of

00:10:18.039 --> 00:10:22.599
questions coming through in the chat, so I'd love to bring a few other people into the conversation

00:10:22.599 --> 00:10:29.080
too. Sep, I see you just asked something around the the workshops too. Yeah, hi Aliyah, my name's

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:34.840
Sep. Thanks for taking the time to share your story with us. My curiosity was around like these

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:41.719
workshops and whether they're going to be mandatory, or is there like a broader program to kind of

00:10:41.719 --> 00:10:46.919
onboard people if you don't mind talking about that would be great. Yeah, I think that's a great question.

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:54.359
And as far as it being mandatory, since we are in public health and COVID is really a huge,

00:10:54.359 --> 00:11:00.280
it's still a huge thing, that we are really sensitive on knowing that a lot of our workforce

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:08.919
is still focused on COVID. So a lot of their time and capacity is really going towards

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:15.719
monitoring COVID and just getting it under wraps within the state. So I think we're sensitive on

00:11:15.719 --> 00:11:23.239
not wanting to make it something mandatory, but the more that we, you know, get this

00:11:23.239 --> 00:11:30.760
this pandemic behind us, then I think that there will be some workshops that will be mandatory for

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:38.599
for some teams, but just really just voluntary. And if you do have the time to come

00:11:38.599 --> 00:11:44.840
and join us, if you have the capacity, but just be insensitive that we are still in a pandemic

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:50.039
and a lot of our workforce are working towards those efforts. That's great. And hopefully if you

00:11:50.039 --> 00:11:55.640
get only a few people, then they can help evangelize and move on from there. Exactly. That's, yeah, that's

00:11:55.640 --> 00:12:03.159
a great hope. Thank you. Frank, I see you asked a question earlier as well, if you want to jump in.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:11.880
I appreciate it, Rachel. Aliyah, thanks. Thanks, like I said, for your time and sharing your

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:16.359
experience, it seems like your initial few minutes just got a lot of activity and got people's

00:12:16.359 --> 00:12:22.760
minds thinking. Where my mind went was as you start to build out these skills and these ways

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:28.039
of thinking around the company, there's going to end up being pockets of information, and then you'll

00:12:28.039 --> 00:12:34.599
ultimately have conflicts and you'll have teams and team members saying, well, people aren't aligned

00:12:34.599 --> 00:12:40.200
and we have people working on the same stuff. And I think in a giant company, that is inevitable.

00:12:41.159 --> 00:12:45.320
I've handled that one way in my own experience, but I'm curious, right, is that something that

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:51.000
you think about and worries you? Or are you like, no, that's way too far down the road?

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:57.960
Kind of where's your mind on that? Yeah, so with the development of our new center,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.880
it actually was to resolve a lot of those problems that we were seeing within the agency.

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:11.239
Because we have a public health organization, it's very interesting. We're all epidemiologists,

00:13:11.239 --> 00:13:18.599
but everyone has their different topic of focus. Everyone has their different expertise. So because

00:13:18.599 --> 00:13:25.000
of that, there are different offices and teams. And what we were seeing was that there was very much

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:33.000
a, just like an array of, like an array and a duplication of things that were already being

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:40.039
done. So this center was actually one of those things that was brought up in order to help us

00:13:40.039 --> 00:13:48.520
centralize across the agency. And thinking about how can we, one, communicate more between each

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:55.559
other, and how can our center be that liaison? So we do have an understanding of what every team

00:13:55.559 --> 00:14:05.799
is working on, and also so that they can rely on us to be kind of this centralized resource for

00:14:05.799 --> 00:14:13.960
them. So I think for us, because we are a new center, that a lot of it is just going to be

00:14:14.359 --> 00:14:24.760
like learning the landscape, and then also sharing back out so others know what other teams are doing.

00:14:25.719 --> 00:14:30.520
So I think right now it's just going to be a lot of communication and a lot of standing up

00:14:31.799 --> 00:14:37.400
of these technologies and getting everyone on board. So I think this is where the heaviest lift

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:44.520
is going to be, but I'm excited to even just, you know, start to communicate and sharing that

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:49.400
knowledge. But I think it's mostly going to be how do we just communicate more and collaborate

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:53.559
more so we know what everyone is doing. Is that mostly email and Slack?

00:14:55.960 --> 00:15:03.719
So right now it's, I mean, right? So right now it is mostly email and then also leveraging these

00:15:03.719 --> 00:15:09.479
weekly meetings that we hold. And these weekly meetings include our health commissioner. So he's

00:15:09.479 --> 00:15:17.320
our health commissioner for the state. It also includes our central office. And then we have

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:24.760
another level, which is considered the district level. So those are each local health district.

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:29.880
So everyone has a representative that is on this call, and everyone has the opportunity to share

00:15:29.880 --> 00:15:36.840
what they're doing. They have the floor to discuss anything that they need. So just thinking

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:44.599
of an example, someone showcased an analysis that they did regarding

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:53.799
COVID cases in schools. And then just sharing that knowledge and giving everyone the floor. So

00:15:53.799 --> 00:16:00.280
I would say right now it's email and it is these like weekly meetings that we've been having.

00:16:01.239 --> 00:16:08.840
Cool. Yeah. Thank you. Thank you. Kelly, I see you also work in local government and had a

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:13.159
great question. Would you want to kind of jump in and add some context there too?

00:16:14.919 --> 00:16:21.559
Sure. Can you hear me okay? Yes, I can. Yeah. So I work for a large local public health department.

00:16:21.559 --> 00:16:28.760
And one of the things that I think would really help us in terms of the pandemic response would

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:32.520
be tracking patients kind of across all of our different data systems. So

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:37.719
looking at our disease reporting database and linking that with the immunization registry to

00:16:37.719 --> 00:16:43.719
see if cases have been vaccinated or not, and then linking that with syndromic data to see who's been

00:16:43.719 --> 00:16:49.000
hospitalized so we can look at breakthrough case rates. But in envisioning, you know, there's the

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.400
technical challenges of linking these systems, but then there's kind of the ethical challenges.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:57.640
And these data systems have different data use agreements. They contain

00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:02.599
more information than you would expect about a given person. And so when you start linking them,

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:09.239
people who weren't originally intended to see the data now have access. And so we're having kind of

00:17:09.239 --> 00:17:16.119
a lot of back and forth about how do we do this responsibly? Can we even do it? And I'm just kind

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:19.719
of curious to hear how those conversations are operating at other health departments.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:33.319
Yeah. So I can speak on specifically in Texas. So that was a huge barrier for us where, like you

00:17:33.319 --> 00:17:40.119
said, Kelly, that because of data use agreements that, you know, we couldn't access, you know, we

00:17:40.119 --> 00:17:47.079
couldn't access a certain agency or office's data, but we were able to access other, like other

00:17:47.079 --> 00:17:57.640
offices' data. And to be honest, I kind of feel like that it should be at a higher level. I don't

00:17:57.640 --> 00:18:05.000
know who needs to mandate this, that there should be easier data sharing. But I've definitely been

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:11.959
in that same position where we were interested in doing specific analyses, but because of,

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:16.520
you know, the people that we were working with that we just could not access that data.

00:18:17.239 --> 00:18:22.040
So it does make our job, like, really difficult. When you know that the data is here,

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:27.079
you know that it's not accessible, but you know that it's there, you know that it exists,

00:18:27.079 --> 00:18:31.560
but, you know, we can't get the agreements in. So sometimes we have to go to legal,

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:38.439
we have to go to lawyers to really build a case on, you know, how are we going to use this?

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:42.760
Why do we need it? So I've definitely been in that same position, Kelly, but

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:47.000
I don't know what the solution is.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:55.000
Thanks, that's really helpful. At least we know we're all in it together.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:01.239
Yeah, absolutely. And then I will say in my current position, because we work with

00:19:02.119 --> 00:19:04.439
aggregate data, so we're not looking at individual

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:09.479
patient level data. So once it gets to us, it's all at the state level.

00:19:13.479 --> 00:19:19.400
Thank you. Thinking more about, like, getting other, like, teams involved and, like, pushing

